statement.p:
Determine if the linear transformation \ltdefn{T}{P_2}{M_{22}} is (a) injective, (b) surjective, (c) invertible.\lteval{T}{a+bx+cx^2}=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                a+2b-2c & 2a+2b \\
                -a+b-4c & 3a+2b+2c
                \end{bmatrix}

Determine if the linear transformation \ltdefn{S}{P_3}{M_{22}} is (a) injective, (b) surjective, (c) invertible.\lteval{S}{a+bx+cx^2+dx^3}=
                \begin{bmatrix}
                -a+4b+c+2d & 4a-b+6c-d\\
                a+5b-2c+2d & a+2c+5d
                \end{bmatrix}

solution.p:
(a) To check injectivity, we compute the kernel of S.  To this end, suppose that a+bx+cx^2+dx^3\in\krn{S}, so\begin{bmatrix}
                0 & 0\\
                0 & 0
                \end{bmatrix}
                =\lteval{S}{a+bx+cx^2+dx^3}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix}
                -a+4b+c+2d & 4a-b+6c-d\\
                a+5b-2c+2d & a+2c+5d
                \end{bmatrix}this creates the homogeneous system of four equations in four variables,
                    -a+4b+c+2d&=0
                    4a-b+6c-d&=0
                    a+5b-2c+2d&=0
                    a+2c+5d&=0
                .  The coefficient matrix of this system row-reduces as,
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                     -1 & 4 & 1 & 2 \\
                     4 & -1 & 6 & -1 \\
                     1 & 5 & -2 & 2 \\
                     1 & 0 & 2 & 5
                    \end{bmatrix}
                    \rref
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                     \leading{1} & 0 & 0 & 0 \\
                     0 & \leading{1} & 0 & 0 \\
                     0 & 0 & \leading{1} & 0 \\
                     0 & 0 & 0 & \leading{1}
                    \end{bmatrix}
                .  We recognize the coefficient matrix as being nonsingular, so the only solution to the system is a=b=c=d=0, and the kernel of S is trivial, \krn{S}=\set{0+0x+0x^2+0x^3}.  By , we see that S is injective.

(b)  We can establish that S is surjective by considering the rank and nullity of S.  We have
                    \rank{S}
                    &=\dimension{P_3}-\nullity{S}&&

                    &=4-0
                    &=\dimension{M_{22}}
                .  So, \rng{S} is a subspace of M_{22} () whose dimension equals that of M_{22}.  By , we gain the set equality \rng{S}=M_{22}.   then implies that S is surjective.

statement.p:
For each linear transformation below:
                (a) Find the matrix representation of T,
                (b) Calculate n(T),
                (c) Calculate r(T),
                (d) Graph the image in either \real{2} or \real{3} as appropriate,
                (e) How many dimensions are lost?, and
                (f) How many dimensions are preserved?


\ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{\complex{3}} given by \lteval{T}{\colvector{x\\y\\z}} = \colvector{x\\x\\x}

\ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{\complex{3}} given by \lteval{T}{\colvector{x\\y\\z}} = \colvector{x\\y\\0}

\ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{\complex{2}} given by \lteval{T}{\colvector{x\\y\\z}} = \colvector{x\\x}

\ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{\complex{2}} given by \lteval{T}{\colvector{x\\y\\z}} = \colvector{x\\y}

\ltdefn{T}{\complex{2}}{\complex{3}} given by \lteval{T}{\colvector{x\\y}} = \colvector{x\\y\\0}

\ltdefn{T}{\complex{2}}{\complex{3}} given by \lteval{T}{\colvector{x\\y}} = \colvector{x\\y\\x+y}

The linear transformation \ltdefn{R}{M_{12}}{M_{21}} is invertible.  Determine a formula for the inverse linear transformation \ltdefn{\ltinverse{R}}{M_{21}}{M_{12}}.\lteval{R}{\begin{bmatrix}a & b\end{bmatrix}}
                =
                \begin{bmatrix}
                a+3b\\
                4a+11b
                \end{bmatrix}

solution.p:
Suppose that we set \vect{v}=\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\end{bmatrix} as a generic element of the codomain, M_{21}.  Then if \begin{bmatrix}r & s\end{bmatrix}=\vect{w}\in\preimage{R}{\vect{v}},
                    \begin{bmatrix}x\\y\end{bmatrix}&=\vect{v}=\lteval{R}{\vect{w}}\\
                    &=
                    \begin{bmatrix}
                    r+3s\\
                    4r+11s
                    \end{bmatrix}
                .  So we obtain the system of two equations in the two variables r and s,
                    r+3s&=x
                    4r+11s&=y
                .  With a nonsingular coefficient matrix, we can solve the system using the inverse of the coefficient matrix,
                    r&=-11x+3y
                    s&=4x-y
                .  So we define,\lteval{\ltinverse{R}}{\vect{v}}
                =\lteval{\ltinverse{R}}{\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\end{bmatrix}}
                =\vect{w}
                =\begin{bmatrix}r & s\end{bmatrix}
                =\begin{bmatrix}-11x+3y & 4x-y\end{bmatrix}.

Consider that
                    \nullity{T}
                    &=\left(\rank{T}+\nullity{T}\right)-\rank{T}
                    &=\dimension{U}-\rank{T}&&

                    &=\dimension{U}-\dimension{\rng{T}}&&

                    &=\dimension{U}-\dimension{V}&&

                    &=\dimension{U}-\dimension{U}
                        &&\text{Hypothesis}
                    &=0
                .  With a null space of zero dimension, \krn{T}=\set{\zerovector}, and by  we see that T is injective.  Thus T is both injective and surjective, so by , T is invertible.

Since \compose{S}{T} is invertible, by  \compose{S}{T} is injective and therefore has a trivial kernel by .  Then
                    \krn{T}
                    &\subseteq\krn{\compose{S}{T}}&&

                    &=\set{\zerovector}&&

                .  Since T has a trivial kernel, by , T is injective.  Also,
                    \rank{T}
                    &=\rank{T} + \nullity{T} - \nullity{T}&&

                    &=\dimension{U}-\nullity{T}&&

                    &=\dimension{U}-0&&

                    &=\dimension{V}
                        &&\text{Hypothesis}
                .  Since \rng{T}\subseteq V,  gives \rng{T}=V, so by , T is surjective.  Finally, by , T is invertible.
